      <hedline>
        <hl1>The World Asks, 'Can We Talk?'</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by City College dean Alfred S Posamentier notes that ever-increasing role of English as lingua franca of world has already had positive effect on New York City schools, which are recruiting foreign math and science teachers who are eager to sharpen their English</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The ever-increasing role of English as the lingua franca of the world (front page, April 16) has already had a positive effect on the New York City schools. The visiting Austrian math and science teacher program in New York City, which I initiated, owes its success largely to the enthusiastic support it received from the Austrian minister of education, Elisabeth Gehrer, who publicly stated her goal to have at least one subject at every Austrian high school taught in English.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The ever-increasing role of English as the lingua franca of the world (front page, April 16) has already had a positive effect on the New York City schools. The visiting Austrian math and science teacher program in New York City, which I initiated, owes its success largely to the enthusiastic support it received from the Austrian minister of education, Elisabeth Gehrer, who publicly stated her goal to have at least one subject at every Austrian high school taught in English.</p>
        <p>What better way to have her teachers' English competence perfected than to have them teach in the city schools?</p>
        <p>ALFRED S. POSAMENTIER  New York, April 16, 2001</p>
        <p>The writer is the dean of the School of Education, City College, CUNY.</p>
      </block>
